    				Photography in India    			


I don√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t understand the restrictions on photography in India.√Ç¬† Today when I went to see my alma mater √¢‚Ç¨‚Äú earlier called VRCE now VNIT (Visvesaraya National Institute of Technology) √¢‚Ç¨‚Äú and was taking some photographs of the main building and other places, I was told that it is illegal to take photographs.√Ç¬† I was told that one can be fined and jailed for taking photographs.√Ç¬† When I asked that there are no signs to that effect √¢‚Ç¨‚Äú I was told that this is known to everybody.√Ç¬† I was given example that somebody took a photo of Nagpur High Court and was brought back from Delhi and fined RS. 5000.
√Ç¬†
Having been to different parts of World with my camera √¢‚Ç¨‚Äú even to China earlier and recently √¢‚Ç¨‚Äú I find this practice intriguing.√Ç¬† In fact I find it so silly that I feel bad about it.√Ç¬† I remember long time ago √¢‚Ç¨‚Äú in 1976 Prof. Nagel in Germany said to me in a conversation about India and other similar poor countries that the problem in these countries is less with material resources more with tradition-bound culture that discourages thinking and changes.√Ç¬† Is that still true in modern India?



