phoenix December 30, 2006 at 12:25 pm 

This is very true. India has a various resources at its disposal, as is very well pointed out by Dr Abdul Kalam in his latest book ‚Äì Ignited Minds, but the people have not stepped out of their shells which tradition built around themselves. Sometimes I feel that many people in India choose to do things the conventional way to avoid the ‚Äútrouble‚Äù taken to think up a different-from-the-normal solution.  Such a behavior, I feel, is mainly attributed to the rote based educational system in India, where thinking is a sin and the ability to memorize mundane details is a gift. Hence, at the end of the day, people want to just finish the task at hand without getting any negative feedbacks from their employer (in any possible way). This was the mindset of the guard who told you not to take any photographs. 
I truly hope that the situation changes, because if India has to progress beyond our dreams, Indians have to think. Think beyond‚Ä¶.








Kunnath Santhosh December 30, 2006 at 7:40 pm 

